@node What "Call 1.11"

     What is it?
     ===========
     
     Call is an CLI program that plays the touchtones in your speaker
     you just specified. 
      
     
     Why should I use Call?
     ===========================
     
     *    Call is easy to use.

     *    Call is small.

     *    Call can send AXE-codes. "*" and "#".
          And if you don't have an AXE-phone at home, now you can use the
          services anyway!

     *    In Sweden we have pay-numbers. At one of them you can put
          an advertisment in one of our nationalwide TV-channels TEXT-TV.
          You do this by sending touchtones. Now you can type all the
          codes in before you dial and send them fast and cheap!
          (I had to put a pause (space) in between every digit... 
           the reciever was probarly too slow)   

     *    Call is cheap (pay if you want)
@endnode

@node How "Call 1.11"

     How to use it
     =============

     Starting the program:
     
     WB:  This program should not be started from Workbench.

     CLI: Type "call xxx" at the prompt.
          There xxx should be your number to dial.
          Type "call ?" for help.
          Type "call * #" for using the AXE-codes.
          To make pauses use space, backslash or minus char.     
     
     The program will play the tones in your speaker in channel 0 and channel 2,
     this because they should be both in the same speaker.

     Ending the program:
     
     Call should end by itself after sending the tones otherwise
     there's something strange going on and you could be in deep shit. :-)

@endnode          

@node Bugs "Call 1.11"
     
     Known Bugs
     ==========
     
     Call doesn't check if the audiochannels is allocated.

     Call uses CIAB timer A hardcoded/direct for timing the length of the tones.

     If you discover more bugs or if you correct one. 
     Please report to the @{" Author " link Author}.
     And if you port this program to another computer, please send that
     program to me. (I can only ask for this...)
@endnode

